        </p>
      </statement>
      <p>Note that <inline-formula><inline-graphic xlink:href="btn603i18.jpg"/></inline-formula>. Since by independence, ‚Ñô(<italic>Y</italic><sub>1</sub>=<italic>N</italic><sub>1</sub>,‚Ä¶,<italic>Y<sub>l</sub></italic>=<italic>N<sub>l</sub></italic>) = ‚àè<sub><italic>i</italic></sub> ‚Ñô(<italic>Y<sub>i</sub></italic>=<italic>N<sub>i</sub></italic>), the theorem follows by rearranging summands. We omit the formal proof.</p>
      <p>The theorem allows us to ‚Äòfold‚Äô mean peak masses of two distributions to compute the mean peak masses of their sum. This implies that we can compute mean peak masses as efficiently as the distribution itself. This improves on the previously best known method (Rockwood <italic>et al</italic>., <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="B15">2004</xref>), replacing the linear running time dependence on the number of atoms by its logarithm.</p>
